Other - The Belle Isle 185, 186 SEL-311L went into ESTUB when Belle Isle 186 reclosed at 20:48:44.027 from the TOC operation at 20:48:00 on the Belle Isle to Hefner to Memorial 138kV line.  This also resulted in the Line Differential Scheme being disabled on the Belle Isle to Thirty Eighth Street to Tulsa 138kV line.  The Line Differential Scheme is disabled to allow line sectionalizing.  At 20:48:50.290, Memorial 108 reclosed into the fault causing the Line Differential Ground Overcurrent element to operate.  Belle Isle 185, 186 did not trip because the Line Differential scheme was disabled.  However, the Line Differential trip was sealed in waiting to trip.  Once the Belle Isle 186 reclosing relay reset, 10 seconds after closing at 20:48:44.027, the Line Differential Scheme was placed back into service causing Belle Isle 185, 186 to trip.  Belle Isle 186 is the lead reclosing breaker for both the Belle Isle to Thirty Eighth Street to Tulsa 138kV line and the Belle Isle to Hefner to Memorial 138kV line.

System Conditions - Chigley 9 did not operate    At 08:55:58 the B phase jumper between OMPA Wynnewood and Shell Elmore City Tap came loose on the Chigley 9 to Pauls Valley 8 69kV line, resulting in an A to B phase fault.  At 9:04:28 SCADA closed Pauls Valley 8.  Pauls Valley 8 should have automatically reclosed 3 seconds after the fault on Dead Line-Hot Bus.  Approximately 8 seconds later, 9:04:36, Chigley 9 reclosed HLIP.    It appears the jumper came loose on the Chigley 9 side since Chigley 9 did not operate again.    As soon as Chigley 9 reclosed, the Paoli to Pauls Valley line relay 50G3 element picked up.  At approximately 9:05:14.598 Etowah 6 tripped to clear the fault.  A few cycles later both Paoli 1, 7 and Pauls Valley 8 tripped.    At approximately 09:05:17.840 Etowah 6 reclosed, and then Pauls Valley 8 reclosed automatically on Hot Line-Dead Bus at approximately 09:05:18.492.  At 09:05:23 Paoli 7 reclosed HLIP.

System Conditions - At 08:55:58 the B phase jumper between OMPA Wynnewood and Shell Elmore City Tap came loose on the Chigley 9 to Pauls Valley 8 69kV line, resulting in an A to B phase fault.  At 9:04:28 SCADA closed Pauls Valley 8.  Pauls Valley 8 should have automatically reclosed 3 seconds after the fault on Dead Line-Hot Bus.  Approximately 8 seconds later, 9:04:36, Chigley 9 reclosed HLIP.    It appears the jumper came loose on the Chigley 9 side since Chigley 9 did not operate again.    As soon as Chigley 9 reclosed, the Paoli to Pauls Valley line relay 50G3 element picked up.  At approximately 9:05:14.598 Etowah 6 tripped to clear the fault.  A few cycles later both Paoli 1, 7 and Pauls Valley 8 tripped.    At approximately 09:05:17.840 Etowah 6 reclosed, and then Pauls Valley 8 reclosed automatically on Hot Line-Dead Bus at approximately 09:05:18.492.  At 09:05:23 Paoli 7 reclosed HLIP.    With the Paoli Bus Tie out of service most of the load at Pauls Valley, Rush Creek, and Shell Elmore City Tap was being served from Chigley.  Once the B Phase jumper came loose, Chigley continued to feed the Pauls Valley, Rush Creek, and Shell Elmore City Tap load on A and C phase but Paoli was feeding the B phase load.  This resulted in a large 3I0 imbalance on the Pauls Valley to Paoli line which continued through to the Etowah to Paoli line.  The imbalance was just above the TOC pickup at Etowah 6.  It was taking Etowah 6 between 15 to 20 seconds to operate for the imbalance which allowed the Etowah 6 reclosing relay to reset between each operation.

Unknown - Hunter 309, 319 tripped with no faults on the system.  The backup SEL-421-5 relay appears to have malfunctioned resulting in Hunter 309, 319 operating multiple times.  The primary SEL-311L did not record any events and did not operate. The SEL-421-5 relay recorded 39 event reports within a 50 second window.  We were also getting Synchrophasors from the relay during this event that shows the abnormal current and voltages coming from the SEL-421-5 when compared to other relays located within the same substation.  After reviewing the event reports and SER data, the relay showed to have fault current and suppressed votlage even after the breakers had opened.  The relay reported having an FPGA error and went through a Diagnostic restart.  Once the relay restarted, the currents and voltages came back normal.  The relay has been shipped back to SEL for further diagnostics.

Human Error - At approx. 17:21 on 6/14/22 Council T116 opened and then went thru its reclosing, after several attempts and a slight delay it attempted to reclose again.      Zac Carlon arrived on site and investigated and informed Ryan Einer of his findings.  Ryan was sent the alarms for Council that TCC was seeing.    Per Ryan Einer:  At this time we believe that the local trip at Council was due to a contractor shorting the CT circuit wired to Bank 2, Bank 3, and T116 and used by the backup 21-132 line relays (138kV Mustang Line).  The contractor was trying to lift and isolate current circuits used by the failed in service Bank 3 transformer and most likely grounded the live CT circuit carrying relay current from Bank 2 resulting in a local trip at Council.  There was no indication of a fault from Mustang relays.  Further investigation will occur tomorrow with the contractor.    Operator Log ID: 70550

Unknown - Notified DCC. At 08:33 1/5/19 the Bluebell / Bristow / Drumright 69kV line tripped and reclosed one time. Receive a report from DCC that a homeowner that lives across from Princeville Sub notice lines glowing. Joshua McKinney 918-863-6313 was dispatched via DCC to investigate the Princeville sub. It took about 20 to 30 minutes to hear back to learn if the issue was at the sub or on the transmission 69kV line. During that period of time. I ran a contingency analysis for opening the Bluebell 6 and Bristow 1 to reduce the flow across the Princeville Tap switch if that may have been the source of the line that was glowing. The CA did not show any issues with opening these two breakers. At 0856 Bluebell 6  was opened to reduce the flow from 22MW to 9MW. I called Chris Broyles and he was notified of the issue and dispatched from Muskogee area to further investigate Princeville due to Joshua McKinney being new in this are, as DCC indicated.  DCC was in contact with Joshua, they informed me that the Princeville goab switches were all good and appeared to be brand new and no arcing had occurred. They further explained that the issues originated in the Princeville sub and was on the DCC side.   At 09:15 1/5/19 Bluebell 6 was closed by scada. The 3 way terminal was restored to a normal configuration. Joshua reported that the switch was good and no issues were observed.   Chris Broyles arrived on site at about 10:50 and indicated that the Princeville Sub was the issue as well, the Princeville Goab switch was good and the line and sub trip were at the same time.
